# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cultured-meat
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting generally follows three steps: pre-bioprinting, bioprinting, and post-bioprinting.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Pre-bioprinting is the process of creating a model that the printer will later create and choosing the materials that will be used.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] One of the first steps is to obtain a biopsy of the organ, to sample cells.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Common technologies used for bioprinting are computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] To print with a layer-by-layer approach, tomographic reconstruction is done on the images.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The now-2D images are then sent to the printer to be made.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Once the image is created, certain cells are isolated and multiplied.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] These cells are then mixed with a special liquefied material that provides oxygen and other nutrients to keep them alive.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] This aggregation of cells does not require a scaffold, and is required for placing in the tubular-like tissue fusion for processes such as extrusion.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] In the second step, the liquid mixtures of cells, matrix, and nutrients known as bioinks are placed in a printer cartridge and deposited using the patients' medical scans.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] When a bioprinted pre-tissue is transferred to an incubator, this cell-based pre-tissue matures into a tissue.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting for fabricating biological constructs typically involves dispensing cells onto a biocompatible scaffold using a successive layer-by-layer approach to generate tissue-like three-dimensional structures.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Artificial organs such as livers and kidneys made by 3D bioprinting have been shown to lack crucial elements that affect the body such as working blood vessels, tubules for collecting urine, and the growth of billions of cells required for these organs.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Without these components the body has no way to get the essential nutrients and oxygen deep within their interiors.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Given that every tissue in the body is naturally composed of different cell types, many technologies for printing these cells vary in their ability to ensure stability and viability of the cells during the manufacturing process.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Some of the methods that are used for 3D bioprinting of cells are photolithography, magnetic 3D bioprinting, stereolithography, and direct cell extrusion.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The post-bioprinting process is necessary to create a stable structure from the biological material.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] If this process is not well-maintained, the mechanical integrity and function of the 3D printed object is at risk.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] To maintain the object, both mechanical and chemical stimulations are needed.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] These stimulations send signals to the cells to control the remodeling and growth of tissues.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] In addition, in recent development, bioreactor technologies have allowed the rapid maturation of tissues, vascularization of tissues and the ability to survive transplants.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Bioreactors work in either providing convective nutrient transport, creating microgravity environments, changing the pressure causing solution to flow through the cells, or adding compression for dynamic or static loading.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Each type of bioreactor is ideal for different types of tissue, for example compression bioreactors are ideal for cartilage tissue.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Researchers in the field have developed approaches to produce living organs that are constructed with the appropriate biological and mechanical properties.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting is based on three main approaches: biomimicry, autonomous self-assembly and mini-tissue building blocks.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The first approach of bioprinting is called biomimicry.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The main goal of this approach is to create fabricated structures that are identical to the natural structure that are found in the tissues and organs in the human body.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Biomimicry requires duplication of the shape, framework, and the microenvironment of the organs and tissues.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The application of biomimicry in bioprinting involves creating both identical cellular and extracellular parts of organs.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] For this approach to be successful, the tissues must be replicated on a micro scale.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Therefore, it is necessary to understand the microenvironment, the nature of the biological forces in this microenvironment, the precise organization of functional and supporting cell types, solubility factors, and the composition of extracellular matrix.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The second approach of bioprinting is autonomous self-assembly.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] This approach relies on the physical process of embryonic organ development as a model to replicate the tissues of interest.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] When cells are in their early development, they create their own extracellular matrix building block, the proper cell signaling, and independent arrangement and patterning to provide the required biological functions and micro-architecture.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Autonomous self-assembly demands specific information about the developmental techniques of the tissues and organs of the embryo.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] There is a "scaffold-free" model that uses self-assembling spheroids that subjects to fusion and cell arrangement to resemble evolving tissues.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Autonomous self-assembly depends on the cell as the fundamental driver of histogenesis, guiding the building blocks, structural and functional properties of these tissues.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] It demands a deeper understanding of how embryonic tissues mechanisms develop as well as the microenvironment surrounded to create the bioprinted tissues.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The third approach of bioprinting is a combination of both the biomimicry and self-assembly approaches, called mini tissues.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Organs and tissues are built from very small functional components.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The mini-tissue approach takes these small pieces and arrange them into larger framework.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Akin to ordinary ink printers, bioprinters have three major components to them.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] These are the hardware used, the type of bio-ink, and the material it is printed on (biomaterials).
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Bio-ink is a material made from living cells that behaves much like a liquid, allowing people to 'print' it in order to create the desired shape.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] To make bio-ink, scientists create a slurry of cells that can be loaded into a cartridge and inserted into a specially designed printer, along with another cartridge containing a gel known as bio-paper.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] In bioprinting, there are three major types of printers that have been used.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] These are inkjet, laser-assisted, and extrusion printers.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Inkjet printers are mainly used in bioprinting for fast and large-scale products.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] One type of inkjet printer, called drop-on-demand inkjet printer, prints materials in exact amounts, minimizing cost and waste.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Printers that use lasers provide high-resolution printing; however, these printers are often expensive.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Extrusion printers print cells layer-by-layer, just like 3D printing to create 3D constructs.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] In addition to just cells, extrusion printers may also use hydrogels infused with cells.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Extrusion-based printing is a very common technique within the field of 3D printing which entails extruding, or forcing, a continuous stream of melted solid material or viscous liquid through a sort of orifice, often a nozzle or syringe.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] When it comes to extrusion based bioprinting, there are four main types of extrusion.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] These are pneumatic driven, piston driven, screw driven and eccentric screw driven (also known as progressing cavity pump).
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Each extrusion method has their own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Pneumatic extrusion uses pressurized air to force liquid bioink through a depositing agent.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Air filters are commonly used to sterilize the air before it is used, to ensure air pushing the bioink is not contaminated.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Piston driven extrusion uses a piston connected to a guide screw.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The linear motion of the piston squeezes material out of the nozzle.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Screw driven extrusion uses an auger screw to extrude material using rotational motion.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Screw driven devices allow for the use of higher viscosity materials and provide more volumetric control.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Eccentric screw driven systems allow for a much more precise deposition of low to high viscosity materials due to the self-sealing chambers in the extruder.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Once printed, many materials require a crosslinking step to achieve the desired mechanical properties for the construct, which can be achieved for example with the treatment of chemical agents or photo-crosslinkers.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Direct extrusion is one of the most common extrusion-based bioprinting techniques, wherein the pressurized force directs the bioink to flow out of the nozzle, and directly print the scaffold without any necessary casting.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The bioink itself for this approach can be a blend of polymer hydrogels, naturally derived materials such as collagen, and live cells suspended in the solution.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] In this manner, scaffolds can be cultured post-print and without the need for further treatment for cellular seeding.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Some focus in the use of direct printing techniques is based upon the use of coaxial nozzle assemblies, or coaxial extrusion.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The coaxial nozzle setup enables the simultaneous extrusion of multiple material bioinks, capable of making multi-layered scaffolds in a single extrusion step.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The development of tubular structures has found the layered extrusion achieved via these techniques desirable for the radial variability in material characterization that it can offer, as the coaxial nozzle provides an inner and outer tube for bioink flow.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Indirect extrusion techniques for bioprinting rather require the printing of a base material of cell-laden hydrogels, but unlike direct extrusion contains a sacrificial hydrogel that can be trivially removed post-printing through thermal or chemical extraction.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The remaining resin solidifies and becomes the desired 3D-printed construct.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Laser-based bioprinting can be split into two major classes: those based on cell transfer technologies or photo-polymerization.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] In cell transfer laser printing, a laser stimulates the connection between energy-absorbing material (e.g. gold, titanium, etc.) and the bioink.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] This 'donor layer' vaporizes under the laser's irradiation, forming a bubble from the bioink layer which gets deposited from a jet.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Photo-polymerization techniques rather use photoinitiated reactions to solidify the ink, moving the beam path of a laser to induce the formation of a desired construct.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Certain laser frequencies paired with photopolymerization reactions can be carried out without damaging cells in the material.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] In this form of printing, plastic residues are melted down and individual layered in sections to create a desired shape.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Nylon and PVA are examples of biomaterials used in this method.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] This technique is most often used to design prototypes for prosthetics and cartilage construction.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Another form of bioprinting involves an inkjet printer, which is primarily used in biomedical settings.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] This method prints detailed proteins and nucleic acids.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Hydrogels are commonly selected as the bioink.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Cells can be printed on to a selected surface media to proliferate and ultimately differentiate.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] A drawback of this printing method is the ability of the bioinks such as hydrogels to clog the printing nozzle, due to their high viscosity.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Ideal inkjet bioprinting involves using a low polymer viscosity (ideally below 10 centipoise), low cell density (<10 million cells/mL), and low structural heights (<10 million cells/mL).
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] There are several other bioprinting techniques which are less commonly used.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Droplet-based bioprinting is a technique in which the bioink blend of cells and/or hydrogels are placed in droplets in precise positions.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Most common amongst this approach are thermal and piezoelectric-drop-on-demand techniques.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] This method of bioprinting is often used experimentally with lung and ovarian cancer models.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Thermal technologies use short duration signals to heat the bioink, inducing the formation of small bubbles which are ejected.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Piezoelectric bioprinting has short duration current applied to a piezoelectric actuator, which induces a mechanical vibration capable of ejecting a small globule of bioink through the nozzle.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] A significant aspect of the study of droplet-based approaches to bioprinting is accounting for mechanical and thermal stress cells within the bioink experience near the nozzle-tip as they are extruded.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Bioinks are essential components of the bioprinting process.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] They are composed of living cells and enzymatic supplements to nurture an environment that supports the biological needs of the printed tissue.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The environment created by the bioink allows for the cell to attach, grow, and differentiate into its adult form.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Cell-encapsualting hydrogels are used in extrusion based bioprinting methods, while gelatin MethacryloylGelatin methacrylon (GelMA) and acellular comprised bioinks are most often used in tissue engineering techniques that require cross-linkage and precise structural integrity.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] It is essential for bioinks to help replicate the external cellular matrix environment that the cell would naturally occur in.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting can be used to reconstruct tissue from various regions of the body.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The precursor to the adoption of 3D printing in healthcare was a series of trials conducted by researchers at Boston Children's Hospital.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The team built replacement urinary bladders by hand for seven patients by constructing scaffolds, then layering the scaffolds with cells from the patients and allowing them to grow.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The trials were a success as the patients remained in good health 7 years after implantation, which led a research fellow named Anthony Atala, MD, to search for ways to automate the process.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Patients with end-stage bladder disease can now be treated by using bio-engineered bladder tissues to rebuild the damaged organ.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] This technology can also potentially be applied to bone, skin, cartilage and muscle tissue.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Though one long-term goal of 3D bioprinting technology is to reconstruct an entire organ as well as minimize the problem of the lack of organs for transplantation.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] There has been little success in bioprinting of fully functional organs e.g. liver, skin, meniscus or pancreas.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Unlike implantable stents, organs have complex shapes and are significantly harder to bioprint.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] A bioprinted heart, for example, must not only meet structural requirements, but also vascularization, mechanical load, and electrical signal propagation requirements.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] In 2022, the first success of a clinical trial for a 3D bioprinted transplant that is made from the patient's own cells, an external ear to treat microtia, was reported.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The limitations of 3D bioprinting are associated with physiologically irrelevant morphology and unsuccessful histological evaluation methods.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting contributes to significant advances in the medical field of tissue engineering by allowing for research to be done on innovative materials called biomaterials.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Some of the most notable bioengineered substances are usually stronger than the average bodily materials, including soft tissue and bone.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] These constituents can act as future substitutes, even improvements, for the original body materials.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] In addition, the Defense Threat Reduction Agency aims to print mini organs such as hearts, livers, and lungs as the potential to test new drugs more accurately and perhaps eliminate the need for testing in animals.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Bioprinting can also be used for cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] In 2021, a steak-like cultured meat, composed of three types of bovine cell fibers was produced.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The Wagyu-like beef has a structure similar to original meat.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] This technology provides an alternative to natural meat harvesting methods if the livestock industry is plagued by disease.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] In addition, it provides a possible solution to reducing the environmental impact of the livestock industry.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The bioprinting of biofilms uses the same methods as other bioprinting.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Oftentimes, the biofilm begins with an extrusion of a polysaccharide to provide structure for biofilm growth.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] An example of one of these polysaccharides is alginate.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The alginate structure can have microbes embedded within the structure.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Hydrogels can also be used to assist in the formation of functional biofilms.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Biofilms are difficult to analyze in a laboratory setting due to the complex structure and the time it takes for a functional biofilm to form.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting biofilms allows us to skip certain processes and makes it easier to analyze functional biofilms.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Thickness of the biofilm being printed with change the functionality due to nutrient and oxygen diffusion.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Thicker 3D printed biofilms will naturally select for anaerobes for example.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Biofilms are capable of remediation in the natural environment which suggests there is potential in regards to the use of 3D bioprinted biofilm use in environmental remediation.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Microbes are able to degrade a large range of chemicals and metals and providing a structure for these microbes to flourish such as in biofilm structures is beneficial.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Artificial biofilms protect the microbes from the dangers of the environment while promoting signaling and overall microbial interactions.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting allows functional microorganisms to be placed in structures that provide mechanical stability and protects them from environmental conditions.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] The larger contact area provided by 3D printed structures compared to normal environmental structures provides more efficient removal of pollutants.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Bioprinting also has possible uses in the future in assisting in wastewater treatment and in corrosion control.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] When humans come in contact with environmental biofilms, it is possible for infections and long-term health hazards to occur.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Antibiotic penetration and expansion within a biofilm is an area of research which can benefit from bioprinting techniques, to further explore the effect of environmental biofilms on human health.
[src:cultured-meat/3d-bioprinting] Biofilm printing requires further research due to limited published data and complex protocols.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] 80,000 Hours advises people to build valuable skills and to apply them to the most pressing global problems.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] Currently, it believes these are mainly issues that could arise from the development of artificial intelligence.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] The book *80,000 Hours* by Benjamin Todd features advice based on the philosophy of effective altruism plus personal fulfillment.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] The organisation has also hosted a podcast since 2017, featuring speakers from a variety of careers and perspectives on such philosophy, as well as a YouTube channel.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] Articles in the vein of the book and podcast have been posted regularly on the 80,000 Hours website since its founding, which also provides advice through one-on-one sessions.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] According to 80,000 Hours, some careers aimed at doing good are far more effective than others.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] They evaluate problems people can focus on solving in terms of their "scale", "neglectedness", and "solvability", while career paths are rated on their potential for immediate social impact, on how well they set someone up to have an impact later on, and on personal fit with the reader.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] 80,000 Hours emphasises that the positive impact of choosing a certain occupation should be measured by the amount of additional good that is created as a result of that choice, not by the amount of good done directly.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] This approach takes into account the concept of replaceability, acknowledging that if one does not take a particular job, someone else likely will, which could alter the net impact of the career choice.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] The organization also questioned some popular career advice, such as "follow your passion".
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] They argued that most people's passions tend to be in areas like sports and arts, which offer limited career opportunities, recommending instead to focus on developing skills in meaningful work, as passion typically develops as a result of mastery and purpose rather than being a prerequisite.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] 80,000 Hours assesses both direct interventions, such as scientific research and policy advocacy, and indirect approaches like earning to give (earning a high salary in a conventional career and donating a large portion of it).
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] 80,000 Hours' primary focus is on advising talented graduates between the ages of 20 and 40.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] It advocates longtermism, the view that improving the long-term future is a moral priority, due to the large number of people who will or could exist in the future.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] Accordingly, the organisation spends significant resources considering interventions perceived to have persisting effects over time, such as improving AI safety or governance, preventing nuclear warfare or pandemics, or enhancing decision-making.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] The largest funder of 80,000 Hours has been Coefficient Giving, backed by husband-and-wife Dustin Moskovitz and Cari Tuna, with cumulative donations of over $20m up to 2025.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] Other significant individual donors include Ben Delo, Luke Ding, Sam Bankman-Fried, Alex Gordon-Brown, Denise Melchin and Jaan Tallinn.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] Organisational funders have included the Frederick Mulder Foundation and the Effective Altruism Meta Fund.
[src:cultured-meat/80-000-hours-podcast] It received $50,000 from Y Combinator in 2015.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Other common names for abalone are ear shells, sea ears, and, now rarely, muttonfish or muttonshells in parts of Australia, ormer in the United Kingdom, perlemoen in South Africa, and pāua in New Zealand.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Most abalone vary in size from 20 mm (0.8 in) (*Haliotis pulcherrima*) to 200 mm (8 in).
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The largest species, *Haliotis rufescens*, reaches 300 mm (12 in).
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The shells of abalone have a low, open spiral structure, and are characterized by several open respiratory pores in a row near the shell's outer edge.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The thick inner layer of the shell is composed of nacre, which in many species is highly iridescent, giving rise to a range of strong, changeable colors which make the shells attractive to humans as ornaments, jewelry, and as a source of colorful mother-of-pearl.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The shell of abalone is convex, rounded to oval in shape, and may be highly arched or very flattened.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The shell of the majority of species has a small, flat spire and two to three whorls.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The last whorl, known as the body whorl, is auriform, meaning that the shell resembles an ear, giving rise to the common name "ear shell".
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] *Haliotis asinina* has a somewhat different shape, as it is more elongated and distended.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The shell of *Haliotis cracherodii cracherodii* is also unusual as it has an ovate form, is imperforate, shows an exserted spire, and has prickly ribs.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] A mantle cleft in the shell impresses a groove in the shell, in which are the row of holes characteristic of the genus.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] These holes are respiratory apertures for venting water from the gills and for releasing sperm and eggs into the water column.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] They make up what is known as the selenizone, which forms as the shell grows.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] This series of eight to 38 holes is near the anterior margin.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The older holes are gradually sealed up as the shell grows and new holes form.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Each species has a typical number of open holes, between four and 10, in the selenizone.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The aperture of the shell is very wide and nacreous.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The exterior of the shell is striated and dull.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The color of the shell is very variable from species to species, which may reflect the animal's diet.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The iridescent nacre that lines the inside of the shell varies in color from silvery white, to pink, red and green-red to deep blue, green to purple.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The animal has fimbriated head lobes and side lobes that are fimbriated and cirrated.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The radula has small median teeth, and the lateral teeth are single and beam-like.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] They have about 70 uncini, with denticulated hooks, the first four very large.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The rounded foot is very large in comparison to most molluscs.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The soft body is coiled around the columellar muscle, and its insertion, instead of being on the columella, is on the middle of the inner wall of the shell.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The gills are symmetrical and both well developed.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] These snails cling solidly with their broad, muscular foot to rocky surfaces at sublittoral depths, although some species such as *Haliotis cracherodii* used to be common in the intertidal zone.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone reach maturity at a relatively small size.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Their fecundity is high and increases with their size, laying from 10,000 to 11 million eggs at a time.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The spermatozoa are filiform and pointed at one end, and the anterior end is a rounded head.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The adults are herbivorous and feed with their rhipidoglossan radula on macroalgae, preferring red or brown algae.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Sizes vary from 20 mm (25⁄32 in) (*Haliotis pulcherrima*) to 200 mm (7+7⁄8 in), while *Haliotis rufescens* is the largest of the genus at 30 cm (12 in).
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The haliotid family has a worldwide distribution, along the coastal waters of every continent, except the Pacific coast of South America, the Atlantic coast of North America, the Arctic, and Antarctica.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The majority of abalone species are found in cold waters, such as off the coasts of New Zealand, South Africa, Australia, Western North America, and Japan.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone are members of the clade Vetigastropoda, though their precise position within the clade is uncertain.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Despite their inclusion in the order Lepetellida, they do not appear to be particularly closely related to other members of the order and may be more closely related to Trochoidea, or alternatively outside of a clade uniting Trochoidea with the rest of Lepetellida.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The earliest known fossil abalone are known from the Campanian age of the Late Cretaceous.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The few known Cretaceous abalone fossils have all been found in North America, suggesting that the group may have originated there, although other possibilities have been suggested, including a central Indo-Pacific origin based on where abalone are most diverse today.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Haliotidae may have evolved from the pleurotomariidan families Temnotropidae or Trochotomidae.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] *Trochotoma frydai*, from the Campanian of Spain, closely resembles the Cretaceous abalone *Haliotis antillesensis* except in having a slit instead of a row of tremata.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The shell of the abalone is exceptionally strong and is composed of a tightly packed calcium carbonate matrix.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Layered among the matrix is an endogenous protein further strengthening the shell.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Due to the unique structure of the shell, a force applied directly to the shell matrix will more likely cause the shedding of layers as opposed to cracking or shattering.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Material scientists are currently studying this structure for insight into stronger ablative protective tools such as body armor.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The dust created by grinding and cutting abalone shell is dangerous; appropriate safeguards must be taken to protect people from inhaling these particles.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone are subject to various infectious diseases.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The Victorian Department of Primary Industries said in 2007 that ganglioneuritis killed up to 90% of stock in affected regions.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone possess very little clotting factor, meaning even a mild to moderate skin-piercing injury can result in death from fluid loss.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Members of the Spionidae of the polychaetes are known as pests of abalone.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone have been harvested for seafood and aesthetics since prehistory.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone shells and associated materials, like their claw-like pearls and nacre, have been used as jewelry and for buttons, buckles and inlay.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] These shells have been found in archaeological sites around the world, ranging from 100,000-year-old deposits at Blombos Cave in South Africa to historic Chinese abalone middens on California's Northern Channel Islands.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] For at least 12,000 years, abalone were harvested to such an extent around the Channel Islands that shells in the area decreased in size four thousand years ago.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Aquafarming of abalone as a meat product began in the late 1950s and early 1960s in Japan and China.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Since the mid-1990s, there have been many increasingly successful endeavors to commercially farm abalone for the purpose of consumption.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Overfishing and poaching have reduced wild populations to such an extent that farmed abalone now supplies most of the abalone meat consumed.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The principal abalone farming regions are Mainland China, Taiwan, Japan and South Korea.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone is also farmed in Australia, Canada, Chile, France, Iceland, Ireland, Mexico, Namibia, New Zealand, South Africa, Spain, Thailand and the United States.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] After trials in 2012, a commercial "sea ranch" was set up in Flinders Bay, Western Australia, to raise abalone.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The ranch is based on an artificial reef made up of 5,000 separate concrete abalone habitat units, which can host 400 abalone each.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The reef is seeded with young abalone from an onshore hatchery.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The abalone feed on seaweed that grows naturally on the habitats; the ecosystem enrichment of the bay also results in growing numbers of dhufish, pink snapper, wrasse, and Samson fish among other species.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone have long been a valuable food source for humans in every area of the world where a species is abundant.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The meat of this mollusc is considered a delicacy in certain parts of Latin America (particularly Chile), France, New Zealand, East Asia and Southeast Asia.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In the Greater China region and among overseas Chinese communities, abalone is commonly known as *bao yu*, and sometimes forms part of a Chinese banquet as one of the four sea delicacies of Chinese cuisine.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In the same way as shark fin soup or bird's nest soup, abalone is considered a luxury item, and is traditionally reserved for celebrations.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In Japan, live and raw abalone are used in sushi (known as *awabi*) or served steamed, salted, boiled, chopped, or simmered in soy sauce.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Salted, fermented abalone entrails are the main component of *tottsuru*, a local dish from Honshū.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In South Korea, abalone is called *Jeonbok* and used in various recipes.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] *Jeonbok* porridge and pan-fried abalone steak with butter are popular, but it's also commonly used in soups or ramyeon.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In California, US, abalone meat can be found on pizza, sautéed with caramelized mango, or in steak form dusted with cracker meal and flour.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] As abalone became more popular and less common, the prices adjusted accordingly.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In the 1920s, a restaurant-served portion of abalone, about 4 ounces (110 g), would cost (in inflation adjusted dollars) about US$7; by 2004, the price had risen to US$75.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In the United States, prior to this time, abalone was predominantly eaten, gathered, and prepared by Chinese immigrants.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Before that, abalone were collected to be eaten, and used for other purposes by Native American tribes.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] By 1900, laws were passed in California to outlaw the taking of abalone above the intertidal zone.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] This forced the Chinese out of the market and the Japanese perfected diving, with or without gear, to enter the market.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone started to become popular in the US after the Panama–Pacific International Exposition in 1915, which exhibited 365 varieties of fish with cooking demonstrations, and a 1,300-seat dining hall.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Tasmania supplies about 25% of the yearly world abalone harvest.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Around 12,500 Tasmanians recreationally fish for blacklip and greenlip abalone.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] For blacklip abalone, the size limit varies between 138 mm (5.4 in) for the southern end of the state and 127 mm (5.0 in) for the northern end of the state.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Greenlip abalone have a minimum size of 145 mm (5.7 in), except for an area around Perkins Bay in the north of the state where the minimum size is 132 millimetres (5.2 in).
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] With a recreational abalone licence, the bag limit is 10 per day, with a total possession limit of 20.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Scuba diving for abalone is allowed, and has a rich history in Australia.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] (Scuba diving for abalone in the states of New South Wales and Western Australia is illegal; a free-diving catch limit of two is allowed).
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Victoria has had an active abalone fishery since the late 1950s.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The state is sectioned into three fishing zones, Eastern, Central and Western, with each fisher required a zone-allocated licence.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Harvesting is performed by divers using surface-supplied air "hookah" systems operating from runabout-style, outboard-powered boats.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] While the diver seeks out colonies of abalone amongst the reef beds, the deckhand operates the boat, known as working "live" and stays above where the diver is working.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Bags of abalone pried from the rocks are brought to the surface by the diver or by way of "shot line", where the deckhand drops a weighted rope for the catch bag to be connected then retrieved.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Divers measure each abalone before removing from the reef and the deckhand remeasures each abalone and removes excess weed growth from the shell.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Since 2002, the Victorian industry has seen a significant decline in catches, with the total allowable catch reduced from 1440 to 787 tonnes for the 2011/12 fishing year, due to dwindling stocks and most notably the abalone virus ganglioneuritis, which is fast-spreading and lethal to abalone stocks.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Sport harvesting of red abalone is permitted with a California fishing license and an abalone stamp card.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In 2008, the abalone card also came with a set of 24 tags.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] This was reduced to 18 abalone per year in 2014, and as of 2017 the limit has been reduced to 12, only nine of which may be taken south of Mendocino County.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Legal-size abalone must be tagged immediately.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone may only be taken using breath-hold techniques or shorepicking; scuba diving for abalone is strictly prohibited.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Taking of abalone is not permitted south of the mouth of San Francisco Bay.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] A size minimum of 7 in (180 mm) measured across the shell is in place.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] A person may be in possession of only three abalone at any given time.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] As of 2017, abalone season is May to October, excluding July.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Transportation of abalone may only legally occur while the abalone is still attached in the shell.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Sale of sport-obtained abalone is illegal, including the shell.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Only red abalone may be taken, as black, white, pink, flat, green, and pinto abalone are protected by law.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In 2018, the California Fish and Game Commission closed recreational abalone season due to dramatically declining populations.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] That year, they extended the moratorium to last through April 2021.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Afterwards, they extended the ban for another 5 years until April 2026.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In December 2025 California extended the ban another 10 years until April 2036.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] An abalone diver is normally equipped with a thick wetsuit, including a hood, bootees, and gloves, and usually also a mask, snorkel, weight belt, abalone iron, and abalone gauge.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Alternatively, the rock picker can feel underneath rocks at low tides for abalone.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone are mostly taken in depths from a few inches up to 10 m (33 ft); less common are freedivers who can work deeper than 10 m (33 ft).
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone are normally found on rocks near food sources such as kelp.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] An abalone iron is used to pry the abalone from the rock before it has time to fully clamp down.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Divers dive from boats, kayaks, tube floats, or directly off the shore.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The largest abalone recorded in California is 12.34 in (31.3 cm), caught by John Pepper somewhere off the coast of San Mateo County in September 1993.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The mollusc *Concholepas concholepas* is often sold in the United States under the name "Chilean abalone", though it is not an abalone, but a muricid.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In New Zealand, abalone is called *pāua* (/ˈpaʊə/, from the Māori language).
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] *Haliotis iris* (or blackfoot pāua) is the ubiquitous New Zealand pāua, the highly polished nacre of which is extremely popular as souvenirs with its striking blue, green, and purple iridescence.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] *Haliotis australis* and *Haliotis virginea* are also found in New Zealand waters, but are less popular than *H. iris*.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] *Haliotis pirimoana* is a small species endemic to Manawatāwhi / the Three Kings Islands that superficially resembles *H. virginea*.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Like all New Zealand shellfish, recreational harvesting of *pāua* does not require a permit provided catch limits, size restrictions, and seasonal and local restrictions set by the Ministry for Primary Industries (MPI) are followed.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The legal recreational daily limit is 10 per diver, with a minimum shell length of 125 mm (4.9 in) for *H. iris* and 80 mm (3.1 in) for *H. australis*.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In addition, no person may be in possession, even on land, of more than 20 pāua or more than 2.5 kg (5.5 lb) of pāua meat at any one time.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Pāua can only be caught by free-diving; it is illegal to catch them using scuba gear.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] An extensive global black market exists in collecting and exporting abalone meat.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] This can be a particularly awkward problem where the right to harvest pāua can be granted legally under Māori customary rights.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] When such permits to harvest are abused, it is frequently difficult to police.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The limit is strictly enforced by roving Ministry for Primary Industries fishery officers with the backing of the New Zealand Police.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Poaching is a major industry in New Zealand with many thousands being taken illegally, often undersized.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Convictions have resulted in seizure of diving gear, boats, and motor vehicles and fines and in rare cases, imprisonment.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] There are five species endemic to South Africa, namely *H. parva*, *H. spadicea*, *H. queketti* and *H. speciosa*.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The largest abalone in South Africa, *Haliotis midae*, occurs along roughly two-thirds of the country's coastline.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone-diving has been a recreational activity for many years, but stocks are currently being threatened by illegal commercial harvesting.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In South Africa, all persons harvesting this shellfish need permits that are issued annually, and no abalone may be harvested using scuba gear.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] For the last few years, however, no permits have been issued for collecting abalone, but commercial harvesting still continues as does illegal collection by syndicates.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In 2007, because of widespread poaching of abalone, the South African government listed abalone as an endangered species according to the CITES section III appendix, which requests member governments to monitor the trade in this species.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] This listing was removed from CITES in June 2010 by the South African government and South African abalone is no longer subject to CITES trade controls.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Export permits are still required, however.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The abalone meat from South Africa is prohibited for sale in the country to help reduce poaching; however, much of the illegally harvested meat is sold in Asian countries.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] As of early 2008, the wholesale price for abalone meat was approximately US$40.00 per kilogram.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] There is an active trade in the shells, which sell for more than US$1,400 per tonne.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Ormers (*Haliotis tuberculata*) are considered a delicacy in the British Channel Islands as well as in adjacent areas of France, and are pursued with great alacrity by the locals.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] This, and a recent lethal bacterial disease, has led to a dramatic depletion in numbers since the latter half of the 19th century, and "ormering" is now strictly regulated to preserve stocks.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The gathering of ormers is now restricted to a number of 'ormering tides', from 1 January to 30 April, which occur on the full or new moon and two days following.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] No ormers may be taken from the beach that are under 80 millimetres (3.1 in) in shell length.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Gatherers are not allowed to wear wetsuits or even put their heads underwater.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Any breach of these laws is a criminal offence and can lead to a fine of up to £5,000 or six months in prison.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The demand for ormers is such that they led to the world's first underwater arrest, when Mr.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Kempthorne-Leigh of Guernsey was arrested by a police officer in full diving gear when illegally diving for ormers.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The highly iridescent inner nacre layer of the shell of abalone has traditionally been used as a decorative item, in jewelry, buttons, and as inlay in furniture and musical instruments, such as on fret boards and binding of guitars.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] See article Najeonchilgi regarding Korean handicraft.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone has been an important staple in a number of Indigenous cultures around the world, specifically in Africa and on the Northwest American coast.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The meat is a traditional food, and the shell is used to make ornaments; historically, the shells were also used as currency in some communities.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Abalone are critically threatened due to overfishing and the acidification of oceans as lower pH erodes the calcium carbonate in their shells.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] In the 21st century, white, pink, and green abalone are on the United States federal endangered species list.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Possible restoration sites have been proposed for the San Clemente Island and Santa Barbara Island areas.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Reintroduction of farming abalone to the wild has been proposed, with these abalone having special tags to help track the population.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The number of species that are recognized within the genus *Haliotis* has fluctuated over time, and depends on the source that is consulted.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The number of recognized species range from 30 to 130.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] As of 2025, 76 extant species and 25 fossil species were listed as accepted in MolluscaBase.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] This list finds a compromise using the WoRMS database, plus some species that have been added, for a total of 57.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] The majority of abalone have not been rated for conservation status.
[src:cultured-meat/abalone] Those that have been reviewed tend to show that the abalone in general is an animal that is declining in numbers, and will need protection throughout the globe.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] ABC began in 1943 as the NBC Blue Network, a radio network that was spun off from NBC, as ordered by the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) in 1942.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] The reason for the order was to expand competition in radio broadcasting in the United States, specifically news and political broadcasting, and broaden the projected points of view.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Only a few companies, such as NBC and CBS, dominated the radio market.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] NBC conducted the split voluntarily in case its appeal of the ruling was denied, and it was forced to split its two networks into separate companies.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Regular television news broadcasts on ABC began soon after the network signed on its initial owned-and-operated television station (WJZ-TV, now WABC-TV) and production center in New York City in August 1948.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Broadcasts continued as the ABC network expanded nationwide.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Until the early 1970s, ABC News programs and ABC in general consistently ranked third in viewership behind CBS and NBC news programs.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] ABC had fewer affiliate stations and a weaker prime-time programming slate to support the network's news operations compared to the two larger networks, each of which had established their radio news operations during the 1930s.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] By the 1970s, the network had effectively turned around, with its prime-time entertainment programs achieving more substantial ratings and drawing in higher advertising revenue and profits for ABC overall.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] With the appointment of the president of ABC Sports, Roone Arledge as president of ABC News in 1977, ABC invested the resources to make it a significant source of news content.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Arledge, known for experimenting with the broadcast "model", created many of ABC News' most popular and enduring programs, including *20/20*, *World News Tonight*, *This Week*, *Nightline*, and *Primetime Live*.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In June 1998, ABC News (which owned an 80% stake in the service), Nine Network and ITN sold their respective interests in Worldwide Television News to the Associated Press.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Additionally, ABC News signed a multi-year content deal with AP for its affiliate video service, Associated Press Television News (APTV), while providing material from ABC's news video service, ABC News One, to APTV.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Scandal erupted on October 7, 1985, over a decision by Arledge, president of ABC News and Sports, to kill a 13-minute report about Marilyn Monroe, possibly due to his close ties to Ethel Kennedy.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] *20/20* drew criticism from the program's co-anchors, Hugh Downs and Barbara Walters, and the executive producer, Av Westin.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Arledge said that he had killed the piece because it was "gossip-column stuff" and "does not live up to its billing." Downs, however, took issue with Arledge's judgment.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] "I am upset about the way it was handled," he said in an interview.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] "I honestly believe that this is more carefully documented than anything any network did during Watergate.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] I lament the fact that the decision reflects badly on people I respect and it reflects badly on me and the broadcast." Additionally, Westin said: "I don't anticipate not putting it on the air.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] We are documenting that there was a relationship between Bobby and Marilyn and Jack and Marilyn.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Fred Otash, a detective who said he was the chief wiretapper, is interviewed on camera, and ABC staff members said three other wiretappers corroborated his account.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In addition, several people not in the book say on camera that Monroe kept diaries with references to meetings with the Kennedy brothers, according to a staff member who has seen the report.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] "It set out to be a piece which would demonstrate that because of alleged relations between Robert Kennedy and John F.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Kennedy and Monroe, the presidency was compromised because organized crime was involved," he said.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] "Based on what has been uncovered so far, there was no evidence." Arledge's decision to kill the broadcast resulted in the subsequent decision of Geraldo Rivera to leave ABC entirely.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Rivera was a *20/20* correspondent but did not work on that story.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] He had been publicly critical of Arledge's decision.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Arledge, a champion and defender of Rivera, said he thought the story needed more work.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] The story probed purported affairs between actress Marilyn Monroe, President John F.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] On August 7, 2014, ABC announced that it would relaunch its radio network division, ABC Radio, on January 1, 2015.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] The change occurred following the announcement that Cumulus would replace its ABC News radio service with Westwood One News (via CNN).
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] On September 20, 2019, ABC Radio was renamed as ABC Audio as the network has evolved to offer a podcast portfolio and other forms of on-demand and linear content.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In April 2018, it was announced that *FiveThirtyEight* would be transferred to ABC News from ESPN, Inc., majority owned by the Walt Disney Company.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] On September 10, 2018, ABC News launched a second attempt to extend its *Good Morning America* brand into the afternoon with *GMA3: What You Need to Know*.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In May 2019, *ABC News Live*, a news focused streaming channel, was launched on Roku.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Following a reorganization of ABC's parent company, The Walt Disney Company which created the Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer and International segment in March 2018, ABC News Digital and Live Streaming, including *ABC News Live* and *FiveThirtyEight*, were transferred to the new segment.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In an October 2018 Simmons Research survey of 38 news organizations, ABC News was ranked the second most trusted news organization by Americans, behind *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In December 2024, ABC's owner, the Walt Disney Company, settled a defamation lawsuit brought by Donald Trump against ABC News, by agreeing to donate $15 million to Trump's future presidential library foundation and paying $1 million in Trump's legal fees.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Disney also agreed to ABC and anchor George Stephanopoulos publishing a statement saying they regretted that Stephanopoulos, in an interview, had repeatedly said that Trump had been found liable for raping E.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In November 2025, President Donald Trump became angry with an ABC News reporter for asking a question about the Jeffrey Epstein case and called for the revocation of the network's broadcasting license.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] The website initially had a dedicated staff of about 30.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In addition to articles, it featured short video clips and audio from the start, delivered using RealAudio and RealVideo technology.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Some content was also available via America Online.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In 2011, ABC News and Yahoo News announced a strategic partnership to share ABC's online reporting on Yahoo's website; the deal expanded in 2015 to include the Disney/ABC Television Group.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In 2018, ABC News, and *Good Morning America* specifically, ended the hosting partnership with Yahoo, instead opting to continue separate web presences.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] The service is under the direction of Justin Dial, Vice President of Streaming Content, Seniboye Tienabeso, Executive Director of ABC News Live, Chandra Zeikel, Executive Producer and Eric Ortega, Executive Producer.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Satellite News Channel was a joint venture between ABC News and Group W that launched on June 21, 1982, as a satellite-delivered cable television network.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] SNC used footage from ABC News and seven Washington, D.C.–based crews and stories from other overseas networks to provide a rotating newscast every 20 minutes.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] However, this channel had difficulty getting clearance from cable systems, so ABC News and Group W decided to sell it to its competitor, CNN (a subsidiary of Time Warner's Turner Broadcasting System).
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] CNN ceased Satellite News Channel's operations on October 27, 1983.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] SNC was either replaced by CNN or CNN2 on most cable systems.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] ABC News Now was a 24-hour cable news network that launched on July 26, 2004, as a digital subchannel by ABC News, being the company's second attempt in the 24-hour cable news world after Satellite News Channel.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] It was offered via digital television, broadband and streaming video at ABCNews.com and on mobile phones.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] It delivered breaking news, headline news each half hour, and a wide range of entertainment and lifestyle programming.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] The channel was available in the United States and Europe.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Its Talk Back feature allowed viewers to voice their input by submitting videos and personal thoughts on controversial issues and current topics.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] It was shut down as a digital subchannel after its experimental phase ended with the Presidential inauguration in 2005.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] ABC News Now was replaced on cable providers with Fusion on October 28, 2013.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Fusion was a digital cable and satellite network owned and operated by Fusion Media Group, LLC, which was a joint venture between ABC News and Univision Communications.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] ABC and Univision formally announced their launch on May 2, 2012.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Launched on October 28, 2013, Fusion features a mix of traditional news and investigative programs along with satirical content aimed at English-speaking Hispanic and Latino American adults between the ages of 18 and 34.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] The network replaced ABC News Now, a mainly streaming service of ABC News content.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In December 2015, it was reported that Disney was in talks to sell its stake in Fusion to Univision.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] The split was complete on April 21, 2016; Univision alone would continue to operate Fusion until December 31, 2021, when it shut down the network.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In March 2024, Donald Trump filed a defamation lawsuit against ABC News and George Stephanopoulos for defamation, alleging that Stephanopoulos's statements during an interview of Trump on *This Week* were "false, intentional, malicious and designed to cause harm".
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Jean Carroll had sued Trump for rape and sexual assault; the jury in the case, *Carroll II*, had found him liable for sexual assault and awarded Carroll $5 million in damages.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In July, ABC News moved to dismiss the case, citing Judge Kaplan's comments that Carroll's rape accusation was "substantially true"; the motion was rejected by the presiding judge.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] In December, after Trump had won the 2024 presidential election, ABC News settled the defamation lawsuit a day after a judge ruled that both Trump and Stephanopoulos were required to sit for depositions in the case.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Legal experts said that the settlement, which occurred prior to motions for summary judgments, was agreed to earlier than is typical in the pre-trial procedures of defamation cases.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] They said that it may have been linked to Trump's status as a president-elect or was negotiated to avoid turning over potentially damaging information in the discovery process.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] The *New York Times* reported that according to company insiders Disney leadership was concerned that a Trump-friendly jury in Florida might potentially award Trump a sum exceeding the settlement, to be followed by a risky appeals process.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] The terms of the settlement required ABC News to pay $15 million to Trump's presidential library and $1 million to cover Trump's legal fees, as well as issue a public apology expressing regret for Stephanopoulos's inaccurate claims against Trump.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] Coincidentally, that country's public broadcasting, the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, operates its unrelated news division that is also named ABC News.
[src:cultured-meat/abc-news-united-states] ABC News maintains a content-sharing agreement with the Nine Network, which also broadcasts *GMA* domestically in the early morning before its own breakfast program.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] The enterprise is a subsidiary of the French publisher Média-Participations.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] Run by president and CEO Mary McAveney, Abrams publishes and distributes approximately 250 titles annually and has more than 3,000 titles in print.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] Abrams also distributes publications for the Victoria and Albert Museum, Tate, Vendome Press (in North America), Booth Clibborn Editions, SelfMadeHero, MoMA Children's Books, and 5 Continents.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] Abrams in 1949, Abrams was the first company in the United States to specialize in the creation and distribution of art books.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] Times Mirror Company acquired the company in 1966 and Harry Abrams retired in 1977.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] For many years, the company was under the direction of Paul Gottlieb (publisher) until January 2001, eighteen months before his death.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] Abrams was acquired by La Martinière Groupe in 1997.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] La Martinière was acquired by Média-Participations in 2018.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] In 2018, Abrams acquired The Overlook Press.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] In 2020, Abrams acquired Cameron + Company.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] Abrams acquired Taunton Press from Active Interest Media in May 2024.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] Founded in 2012, **Abrams Appleseed** publishes board books, novelty books, and picture books for children up to age 5.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] The imprint's list of titles includes *Alphablocks*, *Hippopposites*, *Pantone: Color*, *In My Heart*, and the *Mini Myths* series.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] Stewart, Tabori & Chang (ST&C), a publisher of cookbooks and craft titles, was purchased by Abrams in the late 1990s.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] In what CEO Michael Jacobs described in 2016 as a "unification strategy", all reprinted ST&C titles will appear under Abrams' other existing imprints.
[src:cultured-meat/abrams-press] In addition, a new corporate logo was rolled out simultaneously.
[src:cultured-meat/academic-press] Academic Press publishes books and reference materials in fields including communications engineering, economics, environmental science, finance, food science, geophysics, life sciences, mathematics, neuroscience, psychology, and the physical sciences.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Jason Matheny popularized the concept in the early 2000s after he co-authored a paper on cultured meat production and created New Harvest, the world's first non-profit organization dedicated to *in vitro* meat research.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In 2013, Mark Post created a hamburger patty made from tissue grown outside of an animal; other cultured meat prototypes have gained media attention since.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Most efforts focus on common meats such as pork, beef, and chicken; species which constitute the bulk of conventional meat consumption in developed countries.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Some companies have pursued various species of fish and other seafood, such as Avant Meats who brought cultured grouper to market in 2021.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Other companies such as Orbillion Bio have focused on high-end or unusual meats including elk, lamb, bison, and Wagyu beef.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The production process of cultured meat is constantly evolving, driven by companies and research institutions.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The applications for cultured meat have led to ethical, health, environmental, cultural, and economic discussions.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Data published by The Good Food Institute found that in 2021 through 2023, cultured meat and seafood companies attracted over $2.5 billion in investment worldwide.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] However, cultured meat is not yet widely available.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In January 2024, a study demonstrated that cow cells can produce their own growth factors and do not require the expensive recombinant growth factors or fetal bovine serum.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In November 2025, a study demonstrated that cow cells can be spontaneously immortalized after 500 days without genetic modification, similar to how chicken cells are readily spontaneously immortalized in culture.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Besides *cultured meat*, the terms *cultivated meat*, *clean meat*, *in vitro meat*, *cell-based meat*, *synthetic meat*, *slaughter-free meat*, *craft meat*, *healthy meat*, and *schmeat* have been used to describe the product.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Although it has multiple meanings, *artificial meat* is occasionally used.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The term *lab-grown meat* has been used in news media, but has been criticized on the basis that as production reaches market-scale, it won't be grown in laboratories but rather larger-output facilities which Bruce Friedrich compares to "meat breweries".
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Between 2016 and 2019, *clean meat* gained traction.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The Good Food Institute (GFI) coined the term in 2016, and in late 2018, the institute published research claiming that use of *clean* better reflected the production process and benefits.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] By 2018 it had surpassed *cultured* and *in vitro* in media mentions and Google searches.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Some stakeholders in cultured meat production, seeking to work with conventional meat producers as allies, felt that the term *clean meat* unnecessarily tarnished the latter, and went on to prefer *cell-based meat* as a neutral alternative.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In September 2019, GFI announced new research which found that the term *cultivated meat* is sufficiently descriptive and differentiating, possesses a high degree of neutrality, and ranks highly for consumer appeal.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] A September 2021 poll indicated that the majority of industry CEOs have a preference for *cultivated meat*, with 75 percent of 44 companies preferring it.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The theoretical possibility of growing meat in an industrial setting has long been of interest.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In the 1950s, Dutch researcher Willem van Eelen independently came up with the idea for cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] As a prisoner of war during the Second World War, Van Eelen suffered from starvation, leaving him passionate about food production and food security.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] He attended a university lecture discussing the prospects of preserved meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The earlier discovery of cell lines provided the basis for the idea.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] *In vitro* cultivation of muscle fibers was first performed successfully in 1971 when pathologist Russell Ross cultured guinea pig aorta.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Vein secured patent US 6835390 for the production of tissue-engineered meat for human consumption, wherein muscle and fat would be grown in an integrated fashion to create food products.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In 2001, dermatologist Wiete Westerhof along with van Eelen and businessperson Willem van Kooten announced that they had filed for a worldwide patent on a process to produce cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The process employed a matrix of collagen seeded with muscle cells bathed in a nutritious solution and induced to divide.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] That same year, NASA began conducting cultured meat experiments, with the intent of allowing astronauts to grow meat instead of transporting it.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In partnership with Morris Benjaminson, they cultivated goldfish and turkey.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In 2003, Oron Catts and Ionat Zurr exhibited a few centimeters of "steak", grown from frog stem cells, which they cooked and ate.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In the early 2000s, American public health student Jason Matheny traveled to India and visited a factory chicken farm.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Appalled by the implications of this system, he later teamed up with three scientists involved in NASA's efforts.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In 2004, Matheny founded New Harvest to encourage development by funding research.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In 2005, Jason Matheny, Pieter Edelman, Douglas McFarland & Vladimir Mironov published the first peer-reviewed literature on the subject (In vitro cultured meat production) in Tissue Engineering.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In May 2008, PETA offered a $1 million prize to the first company to bring cultured chicken meat to consumers by 2012.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The contestant was required to complete two tasks to earn the prize, namely to produce a cultured chicken meat product that was indistinguishable from real chicken and produce the product in large enough quantities to be competitively sold in at least 10 states.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The contest was later extended until 4 March 2014.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The deadline eventually expired without a winner.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The Dutch government has invested $4 million into experiments regarding cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The In Vitro Meat Consortium, a group formed by international researchers, held the first international conference hosted by the Norwegian Food Research Institute in April 2008.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] *Time* magazine declared cultured meat production to be one of the 50 breakthrough ideas of 2009.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In November 2009, scientists from the Netherlands announced they had managed to grow meat using cells from a live pig.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The first cultured beef burger patty was created by Mark Post at Maastricht University in 2013.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It was made from over 20,000 thin strands of muscle tissue, cost over $325,000 and needed 2 years to produce.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The burger was tested on live television in London on 5 August 2013.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It was cooked by chef Richard McGeown of Couch's Great House Restaurant in Polperro, Cornwall, and tasted by critics Hanni Rützler, a food researcher from the Future Food Studio, and Josh Schonwald.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Rützler stated, "There is really a bite to it, there is quite some flavour with the browning.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] I know there is no fat in it so I didn't really know how juicy it would be, but there is quite some intense taste; it's close to meat, it's not that juicy, but the consistency is perfect.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It's really something to bite on and I think the look is quite similar." Rützler added that even in a blind trial she would have taken the product for meat rather than a soya copy.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Between 2011 and 2017, many cultured meat startups were launched.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Memphis Meats, now known as Upside Foods, launched a video in February 2016, showcasing its cultured beef meatball.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In March 2017, it showcased chicken tenders and duck a l'orange, the first cultured poultry shown to the public.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] An Israeli company, SuperMeat, cultured chicken.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Finless Foods, a San Francisco-based company working on cultured fish, was founded in June 2016.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In March 2017 it commenced laboratory operations.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In March 2018, Eat Just (in 2011 founded as Hampton Creek in San Francisco, later known as Just, Inc.) claimed to be able to offer a consumer product from cultured meat by the end of 2018.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] According to CEO Josh Tetrick the technology was already there.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] JUST had about 130 employees and a research department of 55 scientists, where cultured meat from poultry, pork and beef was researched.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] JUST has received investments from Chinese billionaire Li Ka-shing, Yahoo! co-founder Jerry Yang and according to Tetrick also by Heineken International and others.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Dutch startup Meatable, consisting of Krijn de Nood, Daan Luining, Ruud Out, Roger Pederson, Mark Kotter and Gordana Apic among others, reported in September 2018 that it had succeeded in growing meat using pluripotent stem cells from animal umbilical cords.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Although such cells are reportedly difficult to work with, Meatable claimed to be able to direct them to behave to become muscle or fat cells as needed.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The major advantage is that this technique bypasses fetal bovine serum, meaning that no animal has to be killed to produce meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] That month, an estimated 30 cultured meat startups operated across the world.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] IntegriCulture is a Japan-based company working on their CulNet system which is a platform that fosters innovation in cellular agriculture by using a feeder organ that works by naturally secreting growth factors that cell cultures need.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Competitors included England based Multus Media and Canadian Future Fields.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In August 2019, five American startups announced the formation of the Alliance for Meat, Poultry & Seafood Innovation (AMPS Innovation), a coalition seeking to work with regulators to create a pathway to market for cultured meat and seafood.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The founding members include Eat Just, Memphis Meats, Finless Foods, BlueNalu, and Fork & Goode.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In October 2019, Aleph Farms collaborated with 3D Bioprinting Solutions to culture meat on the International Space Station.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This was done by extruding meat cells onto a scaffold using a 3D printer.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In January 2020, *Quartz* found around 30 cultured meat startups, and that Memphis Meats, Just Inc. and Future Meat Technologies were the most advanced because they were building pilot plants.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] According to *New Scientist* in May 2020, 60 start-ups were developing cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Some of these were technology suppliers.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Growth media reportedly still cost "hundreds of dollars per litre, but for clean meat production to scale this needs to drop to around $1 a litre." In June 2020, Chinese government officials called for a national strategy to compete in cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Peace of Meat stated in December 2019 that it intended to complete its proof of concept in 2020, to produce its first prototype in 2022, and to go to market in 2023.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] That month, the Foieture project received a research grant of almost 3.6 million euros from the Innovation and Enterprise Agency of the Flemish Government.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In May 2020, Peace of Meat's Austrian-born cofounder and scientific researcher Eva Sommer stated that the startup was then able to produce 20 grams of cultured fat at a cost of about 300 euros (€15,000/kg); the goal was to reduce the price to 6 euros per kilogram by 2030.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Piece of Meat built two laboratories in the Port of Antwerp.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In late 2020, MeaTech acquired Peace of Meat for 15 million euros, and announced in May 2021 that it would build a new large-scale pilot plant in Antwerp by 2022.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In November 2020, Indian start-up Clear Meat claimed it had managed to cultivate chicken mince at the cost of only 800–850 Indian rupees (US$10.77–11.44), while a slaughtered processed chicken cost about 1,000 rupees.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] On 27 April 2022, the European Commission approved the request for the collection of signatures for the European Citizens' Initiative *End The Slaughter Age* to shift subsidies from animal husbandry to cellular agriculture.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] On 7 April 2025, Vow quail became the first cultured meat product to be officially approved for sale in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In mid-June 2025, Vow expected to be serving its cultivated quail in restaurants in Sydney and Melbourne "within weeks".
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In the European Union, novel foods such as cultured meat products have to go through a testing period of about 18 months during which a company must prove to the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) that their product is safe.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In March 2022, cultured meat producers had reached the level of attempting to gain regulatory approval from European Union supranational institutions coming just before mass goods could be sold to consumers.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] By February 2023, none had yet submitted a novel food dossier for approval by the EFSA.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Aleph Farms was the first start-up to apply for approval of its cultivated beef steaks in Switzerland in July 2023.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] While not part of the European Union, Switzerland was regarded as an important case study with great interest from legal scholars around the world, and expected to have widespread implications for the EU countries surrounding it.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In April 2024, the Dutch start-up Meatable hosted the first legally approved public proof‑of‑concept tasting of cultured meat in the European Union - a sausage - following ad hoc approval by a national expert committee under a newly introduced Dutch code of practice.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The event attracted significant national and international media attention.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In July 2024, French startup Gourmey was the first company in Europe to apply for regulatory approval at the EFSA, followed by pioneer Mark Post's Mosa Meat from the Netherlands in January 2025.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The restaurant was not yet fully open to the public, because as of June 2021 SuperMeat still needed to wait for regulatory approval to start mass production for public consumption, and because the COVID-19 pandemic restricted restaurant operations.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] For example, the Israeli Health Ministry and UN Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) co-organised a convention of cultivated food safety regulation experts in September 2022.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In January 2024, the Ministry of Health in Israel granted regulatory approval for cultured beef to Aleph Farms.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] On 2 December 2020, the Singapore Food Agency approved the "chicken bites" produced by Eat Just for commercial sale.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It marked the first time that a cultured meat product passed the safety review (which took 2 years) of a food regulator, and was widely regarded as a milestone for the industry.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The chicken bits were scheduled for introduction in Singaporean restaurants.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Restaurant "1880" became the first to serve cultured meat to customers on Saturday 19 December 2020.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This world-first approval was said to be a milestone in making cultivated meat production more scalable and efficient.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In April 2024, Australian start-up Vow obtained Singaporean approval for its cultured quail; while Dutch start-up Meatable would be introducing its cultivated pork sausages in several restaurants in Singapore later in 2024.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In November 2022, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) completed the pre-market consultation of Upside Foods (formerly Memphis Meats), concluding that its products were safe to eat, a first for cultivated meat companies in the United States.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Approval from the final agency, the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) was received by Upside Foods and Good Meat, both for cultivated chicken, in June 2023.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] On 28 May 2025, Wildtype obtained regulatory approval from the FDA to sell its cultivated coho salmon (*Oncorhynchus kisutch*) product on the U.S. market.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] With that, Wildtype became the first start-up to be permitted to sell cultivated seafood in the United States, and a few days later, it was on the menu at the Kann restaurant of Gregory Gourdet in Portland, Oregon.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] On 6 February 2025, it was announced that British pet food company THE PACK (acquired by Prefera Petfood in May 2025) would release the first commercially available product for pets containing cultivated chicken made by Meatly the following day.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Cellular agriculture requires cell lines, generally stem cells.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Stem cells are undifferentiated cells which have the potential to become many or all of the required kinds of specialized cell types.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Totipotent stem cells have the capacity to differentiate into all the different cell types found within the body.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Pluripotent stem cells can mature into all cell types save those in the placenta, and multipotent stem cells can differentiate into several specialized cell types within one lineage.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Unipotent stem cells can differentiate into one specific cell fate.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] While pluripotent stem cells would be an ideal source, the most prominent example of this subcategory is embryonic stem cells which—due to ethical issues—are controversial for use in research.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] As a result, scientists have developed induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs)—essentially multipotent blood and skin cells that have been regressed to a pluripotent state enabling them to differentiate into a greater range of cells.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The alternative is using multipotent adult stem cells that give rise to muscle cell lineages or unipotent progenitors which differentiate into muscle cells.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Favourable characteristics of stem cells include immortality, proliferative ability, unreliance on adherence, serum independence and easy differentiation into tissue.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The natural presence of such characteristics are likely to differ across cell species and origin.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] As such, *in vitro* cultivation must be adjusted to fill the exact needs of a specific cell line.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The immortality issue is that cells have a limit on the number of times they can divide that is dictated by their telomere cap—supplementary nucleotide bases added to the end of their chromosomes.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] With each division, the telomere cap progressively shortens until nothing remains, at which time the cells cease to divide.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Induced pluripotency can lengthen telomere cap such that the cells divide indefinitely.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Cell lines can be collected from a primary source, i.e., through a biopsy on an animal under local anesthesia.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] They could also be established from secondary sources such as cryopreserved cultures (cultures frozen after previous research).
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Once cell lines are established, they are immersed in a culture medium to induce them to proliferate.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Culture media are typically formulated from basal media that provide cells with necessary carbohydrates, fats, proteins and salts.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Once a cell consumes a sufficient amount, it divides and the population increases exponentially.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Culture media can be supplemented with additives—for instance sera—that supply additional growth factors.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Growth factors can be secreted proteins or steroids that are crucial in regulating cellular processes.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Once differentiation begins, muscle fibres begin to contract and generate lactic acid.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Cells' ability to absorb nutrients and proliferate in part depends on the pH of their environment.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] As lactic acid accumulates within the medium, the environment will become progressively more acidic and falls below the optimal pH.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] As a result, culture media must be frequently refreshed.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This helps refresh the concentration of nutrients from the basal media.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In the case of structured meat products—products that are characterized by their overall configuration as well as cell type—cells must be seeded to scaffolds.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Scaffolds are essentially molds meant to reflect and encourage the cells to organize into a larger structure.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] When cells develop *in vivo*, they are influenced by their interactions with the extracellular matrix (ECM).
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The ECM is the 3-dimensional mesh of glycoproteins, collagen and enzymes responsible for transmitting mechanical and biochemical cues to the cell.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Scaffolds need to simulate the characteristics of the ECM.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Pores are minute openings on the surface of the scaffold.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] They can be created on the surface of the biomaterial in order to release cellular components that could interfere with tissue development.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] They also help diffuse gas and nutrients to the innermost layers of adherent cells, preventing a "necrotic center" from forming.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] A necrotic center is a phenomenon in which cells that are not in direct contact with the culture medium die from a lack of nutrients.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Vascular tissue found in plants contains the organs responsible for internally transporting fluids.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It forms natural topographies that provide a low cost way to promote cell alignment by replicating the natural physiological state of myoblasts.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It may also help with gas and nutrient exchange.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] A scaffold's biochemical properties should be similar to those of the ECM.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It must facilitate cell adhesion through textural qualities or chemical bonding.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Additionally, it must produce the chemical cues that encourage cell differentiation.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Alternatively, the material should be able to blend with other substances which have these functional qualities.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The degree of a material's crystallinity determines qualities such as rigidity.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] High crystallinity can be attributed to hydrogen bonding which in turn increases thermal stability, tensile strength (important for maintaining the scaffold's shape), water retention (important for hydrating the cells) and Young's modulus.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Certain materials degrade into compounds that are beneficial to cells, although this degradation can also be irrelevant or detrimental.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Degradation allows easy removal of the scaffold from the finished product leaving only animal tissue—thereby increasing its resemblance to *in vivo* meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This degradation can be induced by exposure to certain enzymes which do not impact the muscle tissue.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] If scaffolds are unable to be removed from the animal tissue, they must be edible to ensure consumer safety.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It would be beneficial if they were to be made out of nutritious ingredients.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Since 2010, academic research groups and companies have been working to identify raw materials that have the characteristics of suitable scaffolds.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Cellulose is the most abundant polymer in nature and provides the exoskeletons of plant leaves.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Due to its abundance, it can be obtained at a relatively low cost.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Through a process called "decellularization", it is coated in a surfactant that creates pores.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] These pores release the plant's cellular components, and it becomes decellularized plant tissue.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This material has been extensively studied by the Pelling and Gaudette Groups at University of Ottawa and Worcester Polytechnic Institute, respectively.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Through cross-linking (forming covalent bonds between individual polymer chains to hold them together) the plant tissue's mechanical properties can be changed so that it more closely resembles muscle tissue.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This can also be done by blending plant tissue with other materials.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] On the other hand, decellularized plant tissue typically lacks mammalian biochemical cues, so it needs to be coated with compensatory functional proteins.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] C2C12 growth was not shown to change significantly between the bare scaffold and the same scaffold with a coating of collagen or gelatin proteins; however, seeding efficiency (rate at which cells attach to the scaffold) improved.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] An advantage of decellularized plant tissue is the natural topography afforded by the leaf vasculature.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This helps replicate the natural physiological state of the myoblasts which promotes cell alignment.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The other ways of doing this are usually quite a bit more expensive including 3D printing, soft lithography and photolithography.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Vascularization can also help overcome the 100–200 nm diffusion limit of culture medium into cells that usually produce necrotic centres in muscle conglomerates.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Another way to do this is by having a porous scaffold which supports angiogenesis (the development of new blood vessels).
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] While this has been shown to work for apple Hypanthium, not all plants are nearly as porous.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The alternative to plant cellulose is bacterial cellulose which is typically more pure than plant cellulose as it is free from contaminants such as lignin and hemicellulose.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Bacterial cellulose has more hydrogen bonding between its polymer strands and so it has greater crystallinity.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It also has smaller microfibrils that allow it to retain more moisture and have smaller pores.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The substance can be produced using waste carbohydrates (which may allow it to be produced less expensively) and it adds juiciness and chewiness to emulsified meat (which would mean that even if it can't be taken out of the final product, it will contribute to the texture profile).
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Decellularized plants that have been studied as possible scaffold materials include spinach, bamboo, algae, apple, celery, and *Aloe vera*.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Chitin is nature's second most abundant polymer.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It is found in the exoskeletons of arthropods and fungi.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] As cellular agriculture is attempting to end reliance on animals, chitin derived from fungi is of greater interest.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It has mostly been studied by Pelling Group.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Chitosan is derived from chitin in a process known as alkaline deacetylation (substituting out certain amino acid groups).
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The degree of this process determines the physical and chemical properties of the chitosan.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Chitosan has antibacterial properties; in particular, it has bactericidal effects on planktonic bacteria and biofilms and a bacteria static effects on gram negative bacteria such as *E. coli*.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This is important as it neutralizes potentially harmful compounds without using antibiotics, which many consumers avoid.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Chitosan's resemblance to glycosaminoglycans and internal interactions between glycoproteins and proteoglycans make it highly biocompatible.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It can easily blend with other polymers in order to select for more bioactive factors.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] One potential disadvantage of chitosan is that it degrades in the presence of lysozymes (naturally occurring enzymes).
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] But, this can be resisted using deacetylation.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This is not entirely negative, as the byproducts produced through degradation have anti-inflammatory and anti-bacterial properties.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It is important to match the level that cells rely on the matrix for structure with degradation.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Collagen is a family of proteins that makes up the primary structure of human connective tissue.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It is typically derived from bovine, porcine and murine sources.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Cellular agriculture overcomes this dependency through the use of transgenic organisms that are capable of producing the amino acid repeats that make up the collagen.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Collagen naturally exists as collagen type I.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It has been produced as porous hydrogels, composites and substrates with topographical cues and biochemical properties.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Synthetic kinds of collagen have been produced through recombinant protein production—collagen type II and III, tropoelastin and fibronectin.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] One challenge with these proteins is that they can not be modified post translation.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] However, an alternative fibrillar protein has been isolated in microbes that lack collagen's biochemical cues, but has its kind of gene customizability.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] One focus of recombinant collagen production is yield optimization—how it can be produced most effectively.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Plants, in particular, tobacco look like the best option, however, bacteria and yeast are also viable alternatives.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Textured soy protein is a soy flour product often used in plant-based meat that supports the growth of bovine cells.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Its spongy texture enables efficient cell seeding and its porosity encourages oxygen transfer.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Additionally, it degrades during cell differentiation into compounds that are beneficial to certain cells.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Altast Foods Co. is using solid state fermentation to grow mushroom tissue on mycelium scaffolds.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] They harvest this tissue and use it to create bacon analogs.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Nanomaterials exhibit unique properties at the nanoscale.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] London-based Biomimetic Solutions is leveraging nanomaterials in order to create scaffolds.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Cass Materials in Perth, Australia, is using a dietary fibre called Nata de Coco (derived from coconuts) to create nanocellulose sponges for their BNC scaffold.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Nata de Coco is biocompatible, has high porosity, facilitates cell adhesion and is biodegradable.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Immersion Jet Spinning is a method of creating scaffolds by spinning polymers into fibres.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] It was developed by the Parker Group at Harvard.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Their platform uses centrifugal force to extrude a polymer solution through an opening in a rotating reservoir.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] During extrusion, the solution forms a jet that elongates and aligns as it crosses the air gap.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The jet is directed into a vortex-controlled precipitation bath that chemically cross links or precipitates polymer nanofibers.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Adjusting air gap, rotation and the solution changes the diameter of the resulting fibres.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This method can spin scaffolds out of PPTA, nylon, DNA and nanofiber sheets.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] A nanofibrous scaffold made from alginate and gelatin was able to support the growth of C2C12 cells.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Rabbit and bovine aortic smooth muscle myoblasts were able to adhere to the gelatin fibres.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] They formed aggregates on shorter fibres, and aligned tissue on the longer ones.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Matrix Meats is using electrospinning—a process that uses electric force to turn charged polymers into fibres for scaffolds.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Their scaffolds allowed meat marbling, are compatible with multiple cell lines, and are scalable.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Another proposed way of structuring muscle tissue is additive manufacturing.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Such a technique was perfected for industrial applications in manufacturing objects made out of plastic, metal, glass and other synthetic materials.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The most common variation of the process involves incrementally depositing a filament in layers onto a bed until the object is completed.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This method will most likely lend itself best to the application of cultured meat as opposed to other types such as binder jetting, material jetting or stereolithography that require a specific kind of resin or powder.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] A filament of muscle cells can be printed into a structure meant to resemble a finished meat product which can then be further processed for cell maturation.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This technique has been demonstrated in a collaboration between 3D bioprinting solutions and Aleph Farms that used additive manufacturing to structure turkey cells on the International Space Station.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] 3D bioprinting has been used to produce steak-like cultured meat, composed of three types of bovine cell fibers and with a structure of assembled of cell fibers that is similar to original meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Scaffolds are placed inside bioreactors so that cell growth and specialization can occur.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Bioreactors are large machines similar to brewery tanks which expose the cells to a large variety of environmental factors that are necessary to promote either proliferation or differentiation.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The temperature of the bioreactor must replicate *in vivo* conditions.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In the case of mammalian cells, this requires heating to 37 °C (99 °F).
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Alternatively, insect cells can be grown at room temperature.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Most bioreactors are maintained at 5% carbon dioxide.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Cells can be cultivated in either continuous or fed-batch systems.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] The former entails inoculating and harvesting cells in a constant process so that there are always cells in the bioreactor.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Fed-batch systems mean inoculating the cells, culturing them and harvesting them in a single period.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Stirred tank bioreactors are the most widely used configuration.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] An impeller increases the flow, thereby homogenizing the culture media and a diffuser facilitates the exchange of oxygen into the media.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] This system is generally used for suspended cultures but can be used for cells that require attachment to another surface if microcarriers are included.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Fixed bed bioreactors are commonly used for adherent cultures.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] They feature strips of fibres that are packed together to form a bed to which cells can attach.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Aerated culture media is circulated through the bed.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] In airlift bioreactors, the culture media is aerated into a gaseous form using air bubbles which are then scattered and dispersed amongst the cells.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] Perfusion bioreactors are common configurations for continuous cultivation.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p01] They continuously drain media saturated with lactic acid that is void of nutrients and fill it with replenished media.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The culture media is an essential component of *in vitro* cultivation.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] It is responsible for providing the macromolecules, nutrients and growth factors necessary for cell proliferation.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Sourcing growth factors is one of the most challenging tasks of cellular agriculture.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Traditionally, it involves the use of fetal bovine serum (FBS) which is a blood product extracted from fetal cows.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Besides the argument that its production is unethical, it also violates the notion that the cultured meat is produced independent of the use of animals.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] It is also the most costly constituent of cultured meat, priced at around $1000 per litre.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Furthermore, chemical composition varies greatly depending on the animal, so it cannot be uniformly quantified chemically.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] FBS is employed because it conveniently mimics the process of muscle development *in vivo*.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The growth factors needed for tissue development are predominantly provided through an animal's bloodstream, and no other known fluid can single-handedly deliver all these components.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The current alternative is to generate each growth factor individually using recombinant protein production.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In this process, the genes coding for the specific factor are integrated into bacteria which are then fermented.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Due to the added complexity of this process, it is particularly expensive.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Future Fields, a Canadian company focused on overcoming the economic and environmental costs of traditional growth media, is developing serum-free growth factors from fruit flies.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The ideal medium would be chemically quantifiable and accessible to ensure simplicity in production, cheap and not dependent on animals.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] It will most likely be derived from plants; and while this may reduce the possibility of transmitting infectious agents, it may induce allergic reactions in some consumers.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Such culture sera may also require modifications specific to the cell line to which they are applied.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Companies currently invested in developing effective plant based culture include Multus Media and Biftek.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The Good Food Institute (GFI) put out a report in 2019 in support of the concept that cell-based *meat* could be produced at the same cost as ground beef and in 2021 they commissioned a report from CE Delft on the Techno-Economic Analysis of cultivated meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Another proposed approach is to subject the cell lines to a magnetic field, which can stimulate the release of molecules that have regenerative, metabolic, anti-inflammatory and immunity-boosting properties, acting as an alternative to serum.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] A common challenge to bioreactors and scaffolds is developing system configurations that enable all cells to gain exposure to culture media while simultaneously optimizing spatial requirements.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In the cell proliferation phase, prior to the introduction of the scaffold, many cell types need to be attached to a surface to support growth.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] As such, cells must be grown in confluent monolayers only one cell thick which necessitates a lot of surface area.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] This poses practical challenges on large scales.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] As such, systems may incorporate microcarriers—small spherical beads of glass or other compatible material that are suspended in the culture medium.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Cells adhere to these microcarriers as they would to the sides of the bioreactor, which increases the amount of surface area.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In the cell differentiation phase, the cells may be seeded to a scaffold and so do not require the use of microcarriers.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] However, in these instances, the density of the cells on the scaffold means that not all cells have an interface with culture media, leading to cell death and necrotic centers within the meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] When muscle is cultivated *in vivo*, this issue is circumvented as the extracellular matrix delivers nutrients into the muscle through blood vessels.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] As such, many emerging scaffolds aim to replicate such networks.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Similarly, scaffolds must simulate many of the other characteristics of the extracellular matrix, most notably porosity, crystallinity, degradation, biocompatibility and functionality.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Few materials that emulate all these characteristics have been identified, leading to the possibility of blending different materials with complementary properties.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Cellular agriculture research does not have a significant basis of academic interest or funding streams.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Consequently, the majority of research has been undertaken and funded by independent institutions.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] This is incrementally changing as not-for-profits drive support and interest.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Notably, New Harvest has a fellowship program to support graduate students and groups at various academic institutions.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Additionally, a growing number of governments are funding research in cellular agriculture.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In August 2020, the Grant Management Services of the European Commission awarded a €2.5 million grant to ORF Genetics.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] That same month, the Japanese Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry granted IntegriCulture $2.2 million through their New Energy and Industrial Technology Development Organization.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The European Union's Horizon 2020 R&D funding framework awarded a €2.7 million grant to a consortium led by BioTech Foods.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In 2021, the Spanish government granted €3.7 million for Biotech Foods to investigate the potential health benefits of cellular agriculture.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The National Science Foundation awarded a $3.55 million grant to a team of researchers at UC Davis for open-access cultured meat research.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Non-profits also drive support and interest in the field.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Notably, New Harvest has a fellowship program to support the research of specific graduate students and groups at various academic institutions and the Good Food Institute funds open-access research through its Research Grant Program.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Consumer acceptance of the product is critical.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] A study looking at acceptance of cultured meat in China, India, and the US "found high levels of acceptance of clean meat in the three most populous countries worldwide." Several potential factors of consumer acceptance of cultured meat have been identified.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Healthiness, safety, nutritional characteristics, sustainability, taste, and lower price, are all contributing factors.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] One study found that the use of highly technical language to explain cultured meat led to significantly more negative public attitude towards the concept.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] One study suggested that describing cultured meat in a way that emphasizes the final product rather than the production method was an effective way to improve acceptance.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The use of standardized descriptions would improve future research about consumer acceptance of cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Current studies have often reported drastically different rates of acceptance, despite similar survey populations.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Lou Cooperhouse, CEO of BlueNalu, shared on the *Red to Green Podcast* that "cell-based" and "cell-cultured" were suitable terms to differentiate it from conventional meat whilst being clear about the process by which it was made.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] There also exists a challenge in how to use these descriptions in labelling.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] For example, in the United States there is no overarching federal legislation that regulates how cultured meat should be labeled for the consumer.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] While traditional meat producers are attempting to prevent cultured meat companies from using the term "meat," cultured meat producers argue that the word is necessary for consumer acceptance.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Global market acceptance has not been assessed.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Studies are attempting to determine the current levels of consumer acceptance and identify methods to improve this value.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Clear answers are not available, although one recent study reported that consumers were willing to pay a premium for cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Low percentages of older adult populations have been reported to show acceptance of cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Green eating behavior, educational status, and food business were cited as most important factors for this population.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] There is also a lack of studies relating the methods of producing cultured meat with its taste for the consuming public.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Regulatory matters must also be sorted out.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Prior to being available for sale, the European Union, Australia, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, and Canada require approved novel food applications.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Additionally, the European Union requires that cultured animal products and production must prove safety, by an approved company application, as of 1 January 2018.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In 2020, Singapore became the first country in the world to approve cultured meat for sale.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The Singapore Food Agency has published guidance on its requirements for the safety assessment of novel foods, including specific requirements on the information to be submitted for approval of cultivated meat products.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] By October 2023, it was reported the Italian government had retired the draft bill, and withdrew the Technical Regulation Information System notification, a procedure aimed at preventing the creation of barriers within the European Union's internal market, for the bill.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Francesco Lollobrigida, Italy's minister of agriculture, said that the withdrawal of the proposed anti-cultured meat bill Italy submitted to the European Union "is not a step back", which many speculated was because the government wanted to avoid a likely rejection by the European Commission.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] He added that the bill was not going to be retired and would move forward.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Italy became the first country to ban cultured meat in November 2023, when the government approved the bill.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Due to the novelty of cultured meat, there are numerous regulations to regard cultured meat as safe for consumption through several procedures such as evaluation of cell cultivation practices, chemical safety, imports, and toxicity tests.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In September 2020, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) have agreed to jointly regulate cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Under the agreement, the FDA oversees cell collection, cell banks, and cell growth and differentiation, while the USDA oversees the production and labeling of food products derived from the cells that are meant for human consumption.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Firms that are involved in the culturing of animal cells for cultured meat are prompted to contact the FDA in order to begin the process of marketing the biological material.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Despite the strict regulations and efforts put in by the FDA and USDA, there have been struggles in gaining consumer trust and current livestock sector approval on cultured meat, with many states banning and restricting the labeling of cultured meat as "meat".
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Several U.S. states, such as Missouri, South Carolina, Texas, and Washington, have passed legislation limiting the use of the term *meat* on cultured meat packaging.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Full bans on cultured meat have been enacted in Florida and Alabama: in Florida the law makes it a criminal offense to manufacture and sell, and in Alabama cultured meat has been illegal to manufacture, sell, or distribute since October 2024.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The governments of Arizona, Kentucky, Tennessee, and West Virginia are considering similar laws.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In August 2024, Upside Foods sued Florida in an attempt to strike down their law.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Large-scale production of cultured meat may or may not require artificial growth hormones to be added to the culture for meat production.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] As cultured meat is grown in a sterile environment, there is no need for antibiotics.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Today, the widespread use of antibiotics in conventional agriculture is the main driver of antibiotic resistance in humans.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] According to the World Health Organization, antimicrobial resistance represents "an increasingly serious threat to global public health that requires action across all government sectors and society" – predicting up to 10 million deaths annually by 2050.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Cultured meat could provide an effective solution to help mitigate this major risk to human health.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Researchers have suggested that omega-3 fatty acids could be added to cultured meat as a health bonus.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In a similar way, the omega-3 fatty acid content of conventional meat can be increased by altering what the animals are fed.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Research is currently underway in Spain to develop cultivated meat with healthier fats, which could reduce cholesterol and the risk of colon cancer typically associated with red meat consumption.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] An issue of *Time* magazine suggested that the cell-cultured process may also decrease exposure of the meat to bacteria and disease.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Due to the strictly controlled and predictable environment, cultured meat production has been compared to vertical farming.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Some of its proponents have predicted that it will have similar benefits in terms of reducing exposure to dangerous chemicals like pesticides and fungicides, severe injuries, and wildlife.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] There is also a lack of research on the comparison on the health effects of production cultured meat with the industrial meat or the biologic organic meat ways of production.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Although cultured meat consists of animal muscle cells, fat and support cells, as well as blood vessels, that are the same as in traditional meat, some consumers may find the high-tech production process unacceptable.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Cultured meat has been described as fake or "Frankenmeat".
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] On the other hand, cultured meat can be produced without the artificial hormones, antibiotics, steroids, medicine, and GMOs commonly used in factory farmed meat and seafood, though not used on organic biologic production.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] If a cultured meat product is different in appearance, taste, smell, texture, or other factors, it may not be commercially competitive with conventionally produced meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The lack of bone and cardiovascular system is a disadvantage for dishes where these parts make appreciable culinary contributions.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The lack of bones and/or blood may make many traditional meat preparations, such as buffalo wings, more palatable to some people.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Furthermore, blood and bones could potentially be cultured in the future.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Animal production for food is a major cause of air/water pollution and carbon emissions.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Significant questions have been raised about whether the traditional industry can meet the rapidly increasing demands for meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Cultured meat may provide an environmentally conscious alternative to traditional meat production.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The environmental impacts of cultured meat are expected to be significantly lower than from animal husbandry.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] For every hectare that is used for vertical farming and/or cultured meat manufacturing, anywhere between 10 and 20 hectares of land may be returned to its natural state.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Vertical farms (in addition to cultured meat facilities) could exploit methane digesters to generate a portion of its electrical needs.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Methane digesters could be built on site to transform the organic waste generated at the facility into biogas which is generally composed of 65% methane.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] This biogas could be burned to generate electricity for the greenhouse or a series of bioreactors.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] One study reported that cultured meat was "potentially ... much more efficient and environmentally-friendly".
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] It generated only 4% of greenhouse gas emissions, reduced the energy needs of meat production by up to 45%, and required only 2% of the land that the global meat/livestock industry does.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In Tuomisto's life cycle analysis claimed that producing 1,000 kg of meat conventionally requires "26–33 GJ energy, 367–521 m3 water, 190–230 m2 land, and emits 1900–2240 kg CO2-eq GHG emissions".
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] On the other hand, producing the same quantity of meat *in vitro* has "7–45% lower energy use...
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] 78–96% lower GHG emissions, 99% lower land use, and 82–96% lower water use".
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The latest study by independent research firm CE Delft shows that—compared with conventional beef—cultured meat may cause up to 92% less greenhouse gas emissions if renewable energy is used in the production process, 93% less pollution, up to 95% less land use and 78% less water.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] There are many environmental concerns about intensive poultry farming that too can be reduced by cultivating their meat instead of farming animals.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] These concerns include microorganism and pharmaceutical-containing manure entering the water and soil, emission of greenhouse gasses such as nitrous oxide and methane, and the volatilization of manure particles.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Skeptic Margaret Mellon of the Union of Concerned Scientists speculates that the energy and fossil fuel requirements of large-scale cultured meat production may be more environmentally destructive than producing food off the land.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Davis speculated that both vertical farming in urban areas and the activity of cultured meat facilities may cause relatively little harm to the wildlife that live around the facilities.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Dickson Despommier speculated that natural resources may be spared from depletion due to vertical farming and cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] One study reported that conventional farming kills ten wild animals per hectare each year.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Techniques of genetic engineering, such as insertion, deletion, silencing, activation, or mutation of a gene, are not required to produce cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Cultured meat production allows the biological processes that normally occur within an animal to occur without the animal.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Since cultured meat is grown in a controlled, artificial environment, some have commented that cultured meat more closely resembles hydroponic vegetables, rather than genetically modified vegetables.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] More research is underway on cultured meat, and although cultured meat does not require genetic engineering, researchers may employ such techniques to improve quality and sustainability.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Fortifying cultured meat with nutrients such as beneficial fatty acids is one improvement that can be facilitated through genetic modification.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The same improvement can be made without genetic modification, by manipulating the conditions of the culture medium.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Genetic modification may be able to enhance muscle cell proliferation.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The introduction of myogenic regulatory factors, growth factors, or other gene products into muscle cells may increase production over that of conventional meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] To avoid the use of any animal products, the use of photosynthetic algae and cyanobacteria has been proposed to produce the main ingredients for the culture media, as opposed to fetal bovine or horse serum.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Some researchers propose that the ability of algae and cyanobacteria to produce ingredients for culture media can be improved with certain technologies, most likely not excluding genetic engineering.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Australian bioethicist Julian Savulescu said, "Artificial meat stops cruelty to animals, is better for the environment, could be safer and more efficient, and even healthier.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] We have a moral obligation to support this kind of research.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] It gets the ethical two thumbs up." Animal welfare groups are generally in favor of cultured meat, because the culture process does not include a nervous system and therefore does not involve pain or infringement of rights.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Reactions of vegetarians to cultured meat vary.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Some feel the cultured meat presented to the public in August 2013 was not vegetarian because fetal bovine serum was used in the growth medium.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] However, since then, cultured meat has been grown with a medium that does not involve bovine serum.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Philosopher Carlo Alvaro argues that the question of the morality of eating *in vitro* meat has been discussed only in terms of convenience.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Some have proposed independent inquiries into the standards, laws, and regulations for cultured meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Just as with many other foods, cultured meat needs technically sophisticated production methods that may be difficult for some communities, meaning they would lack self-sufficiency and be dependent on global food corporations.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Some projects are focusing on making cellular agriculture accessible to all.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The Shojinmeat Project, for instance, has a bottom-up approach, teaching participants to cultivate DIY cultured meat at home.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Establishing a similar parallel with cultured meat, some environmental activists claim that adopting a vegetarian diet may be a way of focusing on personal actions and righteous gestures rather than systemic change.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Environmentalist Dave Riley states that "being meatless and guiltless seems seductively simple while environmental destruction rages around us", and writes that Mollison "insists that vegetarianism drives animals from the edible landscape so that their contribution to the food chain is lost".
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Jewish rabbinical authorities disagree whether cultured meat is kosher, meaning acceptable under Jewish law and practice.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] One factor is the nature of the animal from which the cells are sourced, whether it is a kosher or non-kosher species and whether, if the cells were taken from a dead animal, slaughter in accordance with religious practice had taken place prior to the extraction of cells.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Most authorities agree that if the original cells were taken from a religiously slaughtered animal then the meat cultured from it will be kosher.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Depending on the nature of the cells, it may be determined to be kosher even when taken from a live animal, and some have argued that it would be kosher even if coming from non-kosher animals such as pigs.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In 2023 the issue of lab meat being a non-meat product or "pareve" has come up for debate.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In 2023 the Chief Rabbi of Israel ruled that some types of cultured meat are kosher, and if not made to resemble meat, can have pareve status.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Islamic dietary practices have also been considered.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Catholicism, which excludes eating meat in certain days along the year (Lent, Holy Week), has not pronounced on whether cultivated meat is banned (as it happens with meat) or not (as with any other food as vegetables or fish).
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Hinduism typically excludes the consumption of beef, such as steak and burgers.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Cultured meat is significantly more costly than conventional meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In a March 2015 interview, Post said that the marginal cost of his team's original €250,000 burger was now €8.00.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] He estimated that technological advancements would allow the product to be cost-competitive to traditionally sourced beef in approximately ten years.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In 2018, Memphis Meats reduced the cost of production to $1,700 per pound.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In 2019, Eat Just said it cost about US$50 to produce one chicken nugget.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The company's cultured chicken nuggets, now available at Singapore restaurant 1880, retail around US$17 as part of a set meal; however, this retail price is below cost.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] As of 2021, most companies report a production cost of $100 or more per meal-sized serving.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] A 2019 study estimated that, with current technology, the actual production cost of cultured meat was over $400,000 per kilogram.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] A 2022 study estimated that, if dramatic advances drove medium costs down to $3.74 per liter, large-scale production costs might optimistically fall to $63 per kilogram over the next few years.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The main drivers of cost would be growth medium (accounting for $19.7/kg), labor ($17.7/kg), and bioreactor repairs ($5.47/kg).
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Competing with wholesale beef ($6/kg) would require reducing all three of these costs.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Food Syst.* addresses the social and economic opportunities and challenges of cultured and plant-based meat for rural producers.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] For instance, Illtud Dunsford comes from a long line of farmers in Wales and established his cultured meat company Cellular Agriculture Ltd in 2016.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In 2015, Maastricht University hosted the first International Conference on Cultured Meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] New Harvest—a 501(c)(3) research institute—as well as The Good Food Institute host annual conferences to convene industry leaders, scientists, investors, and potential collaborators.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The two organizations also fund public research and produce educational content.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Organizations such as the Cellular Agriculture Society and similar organizations in Canada, France, Australia, and New Zealand were founded to advocate for cultured meat in their respective countries.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Publications such as Cell Agri and Protein Report have also provided updates concerning technology and business within the field.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Research continues on many fronts, including entomoculture, interactome maps of cardiac tissue, substrate design, scaffold design, nutritional profile, reaction kinetics, transport phenomena, mass transfer limitations and metabolic stoichiometric requirements, and bioprinting process.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Multiple venture capital firms and accelerator/incubator programs focus on assisting cultured technology startups, or plant-based protein companies in general.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The Big Idea Ventures (BIV) Venture Capital firm launched their New Protein Fund to invest in emerging cell and plant-based food companies in New York and Singapore.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] They invested in MeliBio, Actual Veggies, Biftek.co, Orbillion Bio, Yoconut, Evo, WildFor and Novel Farms.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Indie Bio is a biology oriented accelerator program that has invested in Memphis Meats, Geltor, New Age Meats and Finless Foods.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Cultured meat has often featured in science fiction.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The earliest mention may be in *Two Planets* (1897) by Kurd Lasswitz, where "synthetic meat" is one of the varieties of synthetic food introduced on Earth by Martians.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Other notable books mentioning artificial meat include *Methuselah's Children* (1941) by Robert A.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Heinlein; *Ashes, Ashes* (1943) by René Barjavel; *The Space Merchants* (1952) by Frederik Pohl and C.M.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In film, artificial meat has featured prominently in Giulio Questi's 1968 drama *La morte ha fatto l'uovo* (*Death Laid an Egg*) and Claude Zidi's 1976 comedy *L'aile ou la cuisse* (*The Wing or the Thigh*).
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] "Man-made" chickens also appear in David Lynch's 1977 surrealist horror, *Eraserhead*.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Most recently, it was also featured prominently as the central theme of the movie *Antiviral* (2012).
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The Starship *Enterprise* from the TV and movie franchise *Star Trek* apparently provides a synthetic meat, although crews from *The Next Generation* and later use replicators.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In the ABC sitcom *Better Off Ted* (2009–2010), the episode "Heroes" features Phil (Jonathan Slavin) and Lem (Malcolm Barrett) trying to grow cowless beef.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In the movie *Galaxy Quest* during the dinner scene, Tim Allen's character refers to his steak tasting like "real Iowa beef".
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In the videogame *Project Eden*, the player characters investigate a cultured meat company called Real Meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In *The Expanse*, "vat-grown" meat is produced to feed the people who live on spaceships/space stations away from Earth, due to the exorbitant cost of importing real meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Cultured meat was a subject on an episode of *The Colbert Report* on 17 March 2009.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In February 2014, a biotech startup called BiteLabs ran a campaign to generate popular support for artisanal salami made with meat cultured from celebrity tissue samples.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The campaign became popular on Twitter, where users tweeted at celebrities asking them to donate muscle cells to the project.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Media reactions to BiteLabs variously identified the startup as a satire on startup culture, celebrity culture, or as a discussion prompt on bioethical concerns.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] While BiteLabs claimed to be inspired by the success of Sergey Brin's burger, the company is seen as an example of critical design rather than an actual business venture.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In late 2016, cultured meat was involved in a case in the episode "How The Sausage Is Made" of CBS show *Elementary*.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Cultured meat was profiled in the 2020 Canadian documentary film *Meat the Future*.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In the 2020 video game *Cyberpunk 2077*, multiple cultured meat products are for sale, due to the high cost of natural meat.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] This includes "EEZYBEEF", made from *in vitro* cultured muscle cells taken from cattle, and the flatworm culture based "Orgiatic" which comes in several flavors.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Acellular agriculture is producing animal products synthesized from non-living material.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Such products include milk, honey, eggs, cheese, and gelatin which are made of various proteins rather than cells.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] These proteins must be fermented much like in recombinant protein production, alcohol brewing and the generation of many plant-based products like tofu, tempeh and sauerkraut.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Proteins are coded for by specific genes, the genes coding for the protein of interest are synthesized into a plasmid—a closed loop of double helical genetic information.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] This plasmid, called recombinant DNA, is then inserted into a bacterial specimen.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] For this to happen, the bacteria needs to be competent (i.e. able to accept foreign, extracellular DNA) and able to horizontally transfer genes (i.e. integrate the foreign genes into its own DNA).
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Horizontal gene transfer is significantly more challenging in eukaryotic organisms than prokaryotic organisms because the former have both a cell membrane and a nuclear membrane which the plasmid needs to penetrate whereas prokaryotic organisms only have a cell membrane.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] For this reason, prokaryotic bacteria are often favoured.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In order to make such a bacteria temporarily competent, it can be exposed to a salt such as calcium chloride, which neutralizes the negative charges on the cell membrane's phosphate heads as well as the negative charges on the plasmid to prevent the two from repelling.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] The bacteria can incubate in warm water, opening large pores on the cell surface through which the plasmid can enter.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Next, the bacteria is fermented in sugar, which encourages it to grow and duplicate.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] In the process it expresses its DNA as well as the transferred plasmid resulting in protein.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Finally, the solution is purified to separate out the residual protein.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] This can be done by introducing an antibody raised against the protein of interest that will kill bacteria cells that do not contain the protein.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Through centrifugation, the solution can be spun around an axis with sufficient force to separate solids from liquids.
[src:cultured-meat/cultured-meat-p02] Alternatively it could be soaked in a buffered ionic solution that employs osmosis to leach the water from bacteria and kill them.
